.TH "socklog\-conf" "8" 
.SH NAME
socklog\-conf \- sets up a socklog(8) service.
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]socklog\-conf\f[R] unix|inet|klog|ucspi\-tcp \f[I]acct\f[R]
\f[I]logacct\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\f[B]socklog\-conf\f[R] notify \f[I]acct\f[R] \f[I]grp\f[R]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]socklog\-conf\f[R] creates \f[I]/etc/sv\f[R] if necessary and a
subdirectory that runs the \f[B]unix\f[R], \f[B]inet\f[R],
\f[B]ucspi\-tcp\f[R] or \f[B]notify\f[R] service (see below for each
service).
Except for the notify service, \f[B]socklog\-conf\f[R] also creates a
log directory with subdirectories.
.PP
\f[I]acct\f[R], \f[I]logacct\f[R] and \f[I]grp\f[R] must not contain any
special characters.
.SH UNIX SERVICE
\f[B]socklog\-conf\f[R] unix \f[I]acct\f[R] \f[I]logacct\f[R]
.PP
Running \f[B]socklog\-conf\f[R] with the 1st argument \f[I]unix\f[R],
\f[B]socklog\-conf\f[R] creates the service directory
\f[I]/etc/sv/socklog\-unix\f[R] and the log directory
\f[I]/var/log/socklog\f[R].
.PP
\f[B]socklog\-conf\f[R] arranges for \f[B]socklog\f[R](8) to run under
the uid and gid of \f[I]acct\f[R] and to listen for syslog messages on
\f[I]/dev/log\f[R].
.PP
It also creates automatically rotated log directories in
\f[I]/var/log/socklog\f[R].
The logs are owned by \f[I]logacct\f[R].
The corresponding \f[B]svlogd\f[R](8) process runs under the uid and gid
of \f[I]logacct\f[R].
.PP
You can run the service under \f[B]runsvdir\f[R](8) by creating a
symbolic link in the services directory:
.PP
ln \-s /etc/sv/socklog\-unix /service/
.SH INET SERVICE
\f[B]socklog\-conf\f[R] inet \f[I]acct\f[R] \f[I]logacct\f[R]
.PP
Running \f[B]socklog\-conf\f[R] with the 1st argument \f[I]inet\f[R],
\f[B]socklog\-conf\f[R] creates the service directory
\f[I]/etc/sv/socklog\-inet\f[R] and the log directory
\f[I]/var/log/socklog\-inet\f[R].
.PP
\f[B]socklog\-conf\f[R] arranges for \f[B]socklog\f[R](8) to run under
the uid and gid of \f[I]acct\f[R] and to listen for syslog messages on
the UDP socket \f[I]0.0.0.0:514\f[R].
.PP
It also creates automatically rotated log directories in
\f[I]/var/log/socklog\-inet\f[R].
The logs are owned by \f[I]logacct\f[R].
The corresponding \f[B]svlogd\f[R](8) process runs under the uid and gid
of \f[I]logacct\f[R].
.PP
You can run the service under \f[B]runsvdir\f[R](8) by creating a
symbolic link in the services directory:
.PP
ln \-s /etc/sv/socklog\-inet /service/
.SH KLOG SERVICE
\f[B]socklog\-conf\f[R] klog \f[I]acct\f[R] \f[I]logacct\f[R]
.PP
Running \f[B]socklog\-conf\f[R] with the 1st argument \f[I]klog\f[R],
\f[B]socklog\-conf\f[R] creates the service directory
\f[I]/etc/sv/socklog\-klog\f[R] and the log directory
\f[I]/var/log/socklog\-klog\f[R].
.PP
\f[B]socklog\-conf\f[R] arranges for \f[B]socklog\f[R](8) to run under
the uid and gid of \f[I]acct\f[R] and to read kernel messages from
\f[I]/proc/kmsg\f[R] on Linux, or \f[I]/dev/socklog\-klog\f[R] on BSD.
.PP
It also creates automatically rotated log directories in
\f[I]/var/log/socklog\-klog\f[R].
The logs are owned by \f[I]logacct\f[R].
The corresponding \f[B]svlogd\f[R](8) process runs under the uid and gid
of \f[I]logacct\f[R].
.PP
You can run the service under \f[B]runsvdir\f[R](8) by creating a
symbolic link in the services directory:
.PP
ln \-s /etc/sv/socklog\-klog /service/
.SH UCSPI\-TCP SERVICE
\f[B]socklog\-conf\f[R] ucspi\-tcp \f[I]acct\f[R] \f[I]logacct\f[R]
.PP
Running \f[B]socklog\-conf\f[R] with the 1st argument
\f[I]ucspi\-tcp\f[R], \f[B]socklog\-conf\f[R] creates the service
directory \f[I]/etc/sv/socklog\-ucspi\-tcp\f[R] and the log directory
\f[I]/var/log/socklog\-ucspi\-tcp\f[R].
.PP
\f[B]socklog\-conf\f[R] arranges for \f[B]tcpsvd\f[R](1) to run
\f[B]socklog\f[R](8) under the uid and gid of \f[I]acct\f[R] and to
listen on the TCP socket \f[I]0.0.0.0:10116\f[R].
.PP
It also creates automatically rotated log directories in
\f[I]/var/log/socklog\-ucspi\-tcp\f[R].
The logs are owned by \f[I]logacct\f[R].
The corresponding \f[B]svlogd\f[R](8) process runs under the uid and gid
of \f[I]logacct\f[R].
.PP
You can run the service under \f[B]runsvdir\f[R](8) by creating a
symbolic link in the services directory:
.PP
ln \-s /etc/sv/socklog\-ucspi\-tcp /service/
.SH NOTIFY SERVICE
\f[B]socklog\-conf\f[R] notify \f[I]acct\f[R] \f[I]grp\f[R]
.PP
Running \f[B]socklog\-conf\f[R] with the 1st argument \f[I]notify\f[R],
\f[B]socklog\-conf\f[R] creates the service directory
\f[I]/etc/sv/socklog\-notify\f[R].
.PP
\f[B]socklog\-conf\f[R] arranges for \f[B]uncat\f[R](1) to run under the
uid and gid of \f[I]acct\f[R] and to listen on the named pipe
\f[I]/var/log/socklog/.notify\f[R].
The named pipe will have mode 0620, the uid of \f[I]acct\f[R] and the
gid of \f[I]grp\f[R].
.PP
All uids running a log service that is configured to push log events to
the socklog\-notify service must be member of the group \f[I]grp\f[R].
.PP
You can run the service under \f[B]runsvdir\f[R](8) by creating a
symbolic link in the services directory:
.PP
ln \-s /etc/sv/socklog\-notify /service/
